This is still complicated. Let's try a simpler approach. We need to show that `eLorentzNorm f p 1 őľ < ‚ä§`.

The induction hypothesis `hf` is:
`eLpNorm (T f) 1 (őĹ.restrict G) ‚Č§ (4 * ‚ÜĎc / p) * eLorentzNorm f p 1 őľ * őĹ G ^ p'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal`

The left side `eLpNorm (T f) 1 (őĹ.restrict G)` is finite because `T f` is strongly measurable and `őĹ.restrict G` is finite (from `hG' : őĹ G < ‚ä§`). Therefore, the right side must also be finite.

So `(4 * ‚ÜĎc / p) * eLorentzNorm f p 1 őľ * őĹ G ^ p'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal < ‚ä§`.

From this, we can deduce that `eLorentzNorm f p 1 őľ < ‚ä§` because `4 * c / p > 0` (since `c > 0` and `p ‚Č• 1`), `őĹ G ^ p'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal > 0` (since `őĹ G ‚Č• 0` and `p' ‚Č• 1`), and `p'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal > 0`.

